You have two options: **(a)** I can run the scan commands for you here if you say "go ahead", or **(b)** you can copy and paste them and run them yourself on that Windows laptop.

If you prefer option (b), here’s a PowerShell command that searches for Electrum wallet files by their internal signature (`BIE1` prefix – encrypted wallets) and also looks for common filenames. **Run it in PowerShell as Administrator** (right-click PowerShell, "Run as Administrator") to scan protected folders.

```powershell
# Scan default Electrum directory and USB drives
$paths = @("$env:APPDATA\Electrum\wallets", "D:\", "E:\", "F:\")
foreach ($p in $paths) {
    if (Test-Path $p) {
        Write-Host "Scanning $p ..."
        Get-ChildItem -Path $p -Recurse -File | Where-Object {
            $_.Length -gt 100 -and $_.Length -lt 1MB
        } | Select-String "BIE1" -SimpleMatch -Quiet | ForEach-Object {
            $_.Path
        }
    }
}
```

This will list candidate wallet file paths. Alternatively, if you'd rather just find files named `default_wallet` or `*.wallet` (Electrum often uses no extension), run:

```powershell
Get-ChildItem -Path @("$env:APPDATA\Electrum\wallets", "D:\", "E:\", "F:\") -Recurse -Include "*wallet*", "*.wallet" | Select-Object FullName, Length
```

Let me know which option you'd like. If you choose option (a), I'll run the scan from here once you say "go ahead".
